== Description of the Object

This project is a hand-pushed burin engraving on a hammered copper plate
depicting the biblical scene of Saul's conversion on the road to Damascus
(Acts 9:1–9). The engraving is executed using period-accurate tools, materials,
and techniques consistent with the practice of European goldsmith-engravers of
the 15th–16th centuries. The finished plate serves as both a decorative
engraved object and a functional intaglio printing plate from which paper
impressions can be pulled.

== Skills Required

This project requires the integration of multiple distinct skills: metallurgy
and tool-making (forging, hardening, and tempering steel gravers from
high-carbon tool steel); woodturning (turning graver handles from dense
hardwood on a lathe); metalwork (hammering and polishing the copper plate);
draftsmanship (converting a painted source image into a reversed line drawing
suitable for engraving); design transfer (applying the reversed drawing to the
polished plate using period transfer methods); push engraving (cutting lines,
hatching, cross-hatching, and stippling with a burin using hand pressure
only); sharpening (maintaining precise cutting geometry on synthetic
waterstones and a leather strop); and, optionally, intaglio printing
(inking, wiping, and pressing the plate to produce paper impressions).

== The Biblical Subject

The Conversion of Saul on the Road to Damascus is recorded in Acts 9:1–9, with
parallel accounts in Acts 22:6–11 and Acts 26:12–18 @acts-of-the-apostles.
Saul of Tarsus, a persecutor of the early Christian community, is traveling to
Damascus with letters authorizing the arrest of Christians. Near the city, a
brilliant light from heaven strikes him to the ground and he hears a voice:
"Saul, Saul, why do you persecute me?" Blinded, Saul is led into Damascus,
where after three days his sight is restored and he is baptized, becoming
Paul the Apostle.

The scene attracted repeated treatment by major artists across the long
sixteenth century, on both sides of the Alps and in both print and paint:
Lucas van Leyden's burin engraving of 1509 @met-lucas-conversion, Hans
Baldung Grien's woodcut of c. 1515–17 @bm-baldung-conversion, Parmigianino's
oil of c. 1527–28 @khm-parmigianino-conversion, Moretto da Brescia's
_Conversion of Saint Paul_ of c. 1540–41 on a vault of the ambulatory of
Santa Maria presso San Celso in Milan @moretto-conversion, Michelangelo's
fresco in the Cappella Paolina (c. 1542–45) @wallace-pauline-chapel, and
Jacopo Tintoretto's painting of c. 1544 together span the century and the
principal pictorial media of the period. The National Gallery of Art,
in its catalog entry on Tintoretto's _Conversion of Saint Paul_, notes that
"from a religious perspective, the image of Christ winning over Saul
represented divine power and specifically the victory of the Church over
its enemies" and that "for artists, the story provided an opportunity to
show off their skills in what often came to be treated as a battle scene"
@nga-tintoretto-conversion.

== Historical Exemplars

The following are documented, extant historical exemplars demonstrating that
push engraving of biblical scenes on copper was a well-established practice
throughout the 15th and 16th centuries. These exemplars span multiple
geographic regions, artistic traditions, and decades, providing compelling
evidence that this project replicates an authentic period craft.

=== Exemplar 1: Martin Schongauer, Passion Series (c. 1475–1480)

A series of twelve burin engravings on copper depicting scenes from the
Passion of Christ. Schongauer (c. 1450–1491) was the son of a Colmar
goldsmith and the most important printmaker north of the Alps before Dürer.
The canonical catalogue raisonné of his prints — Max Lehrs's 1925 volume
devoted entirely to Schongauer in the _Geschichte und kritischer Katalog des
deutschen, niederländischen und französischen Kupferstichs im XV. Jahrhundert_
— documents the 116 surviving engravings that were distributed across Europe
@lehrs-1925. The Passion series exemplifies the practice of engraving
biblical narrative scenes for devotional use. Impressions are held at the British Museum, the Victoria and
Albert Museum, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, and other major print
collections worldwide. As Paula Nuttall writes for the V&A,
"The Resurrection comes from a series of twelve engravings of The Passion of
Christ" @va-schongauer-resurrection.

=== Exemplar 2: Albrecht Dürer, The Three Master Engravings (1513–1514)

Three burin engravings on copper: _Knight, Death and the Devil_ (1513),
_St. Jerome in His Study_ (1514), and _Melencolia I_ (1514). These represent
the highest technical achievement of pre-1600 push engraving. Dürer
(1471–1528) learned burin technique from his goldsmith father and perfected
it over decades. The engravings demonstrate the full expressive range of the
burin — line, hatching, cross-hatching, and stippling — applied to complex
figurative and symbolic compositions. Impressions are held in numerous major
print collections worldwide, including the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the
British Museum, and the Rijksmuseum. Erwin Panofsky's _The Life and Art of
Albrecht Dürer_ — the canonical scholarly biography — traces Dürer's
command of the burin to the goldsmith training he received in his father's
Nuremberg workshop, treating burin technique as a skill continuous with the
goldsmith's trade rather than an independent pictorial art @panofsky-durer.
Landau and Parshall's _The Renaissance Print, 1470–1550_
treats Dürer's transition from his father's goldsmith shop to independent
print publication as the canonical case of the late-15th-century
goldsmith-to-engraver pathway @landau-parshall.

=== Exemplar 3: Maso Finiguerra, Niello Paxes (c. 1452–1464)

Engraved silver paxes with niello fill, produced for the Florence Baptistery.
Finiguerra (1426–1464) was a Florentine goldsmith. Sidney Colvin, in his
signed entry on Finiguerra in the 1911 _Encyclopædia Britannica_, paraphrases
Cellini's praise of Finiguerra as the finest master of his day in niello
engraving @colvin-finiguerra-eb1911. His work demonstrates that engraving of
religious scenes on metal — for liturgical rather than printing purposes —
was standard goldsmith's practice in 15th-century Italy. Sulfur casts and
paper impressions taken from his engraved plates survive, documenting the
practice of recording engraved designs. Vasari, in the _Life of Marcantonio
Bolognese_ in the 1568 edition of the _Vite_, credits Finiguerra with taking
impressions from his engraved silver plates on paper and so first revealing
that engraved metal could be printed @vasari-bondanella. Niello paxes
are held at the Museo Nazionale del Bargello, Florence; sulfur casts at the
British Museum; niello plaques at the Metropolitan Museum of Art.

=== Exemplar 4: Hans Baldung Grien, The Conversion of St. Paul, woodcut (c. 1515–17)

A single-sheet woodcut depicting the same biblical subject as this project.
From the British Museum image, the composition shows Paul and his horse
fallen, two mounted companions, and Christ in the clouds (the upper figure
appears to hold a tau-shaped cross — a visual observation rather than a
detail confirmed in the museum record). While a woodcut rather than an
engraving, this demonstrates that the Conversion of Paul was an established
subject for printmakers in the early 16th century. The bold composition and
dramatic treatment of the scene provide a period model for the subject. The
British Museum collection record describes it as "the Conversion of St Paul;
St Paul and his horse on the ground, struck and blinded by the bright light
which is set against a dark sky and sent by Christ" @bm-baldung-conversion.

=== Exemplar 5: Lucas van Leyden, The Conversion of St. Paul, engraving

A burin engraving on copper depicting the same subject. Lucas van Leyden
(1494–1533) was one of the leading engravers of the Low Countries. This
exemplar is directly relevant because it is both an intaglio burin engraving
and depicts the identical biblical scene, demonstrating that the Conversion
of Paul was an established subject for copper-plate engravers
@met-lucas-conversion.

=== Additional Evidence of Use and Purpose

Engraved devotional prints served documented purposes in the 15th–16th
centuries: as affordable alternatives to painted devotional images for
middle-class buyers; as personal devotional aids that could be inserted into
prayer books; as commercial products sold individually or in series; and as
pattern sources for other artists working in painting, sculpture, and other
media. The V&A notes that "printed images on paper were to some extent
inexpensive alternatives to paintings" @va-schongauer-resurrection.
Landau and Parshall observe that serving as a pattern for other artists
working in painting, sculpture, and the decorative arts was itself one of
the primary purposes for which many Renaissance prints were produced
@landau-parshall. Goldsmiths also engraved directly onto
liturgical objects (chalices, paxes, reliquaries) for ecclesiastical use,
and onto secular objects (armor, jewelry, belt fittings) for decorative
purposes.
